steps.instruction:
Emit a compact JSON index of the current Obsidian state for this project. You have MCP tools: mcp__obsidian-projects__list_files, mcp__obsidian-projects__read_file.

1. Parse base_path and slug from the read-shelf-config output.
2. Verify the project dashboard exists: mcp__obsidian-projects__read_file({ path: "{base_path}/{slug}/{slug}.md" }). If it does NOT exist, write this exact JSON to your output file and stop:
   {"project_exists": false, "base_path": "{base_path}", "slug": "{slug}", "issues": [], "docs": [], "dashboard": null}
3. List existing issue notes: mcp__obsidian-projects__list_files({ path: "{base_path}/{slug}/issues" }). For each .md file returned, read it and extract from the YAML frontmatter ONLY these fields: last_synced, status, github_number, source, type. Do NOT include the body. Record filename_slug (filename without .md) and full path.
4. List existing doc notes: mcp__obsidian-projects__list_files({ path: "{base_path}/{slug}/docs" }). For each .md file, read it and extract last_synced, prd_path, type from frontmatter. Do NOT include the body.
5. From the dashboard file already read in step 2, extract its full frontmatter object. Also scan the body for top-level '## ' headings and record ONLY the heading names (not the content under them).
6. Emit this exact JSON shape to the output file:
   {
     "project_exists": true,
     "base_path": "{base_path}",
     "slug": "{slug}",
     "dashboard": {
       "frontmatter": { ... full frontmatter ... },
       "section_headings": ["Section Name", ...]
     },
     "issues": [
       {"path": "...", "filename_slug": "...", "last_synced": "...", "status": "...", "github_number": N_or_null, "source": "..."}
     ],
     "docs": [
       {"path": "...", "filename_slug": "...", "last_synced": "...", "prd_path": "..."}
     ]
   }

IMPORTANT: Your output must be valid JSON parseable by `jq .`. Do not include any note body content. Do not fetch GitHub issues or PRDs — that is not your job. You only list what is already in Obsidian.
